The energy of one mole of photons with a wavelength of 300 nm is calculated using the formula for photon energy and Avogadro's number. The energy per photon is given by \(E = \frac{hc}{\lambda}\), where \(h\) is Planck's constant (\(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s}\)), \(c\) is the speed of light (\(3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s}\)), and \(\lambda\) is the wavelength in meters (300 nm = \(3.00 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}\)).

First, compute the energy per photon:
\[
E_{\text{photon}} = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8)}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 6.626 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J}
\]

Then, multiply by Avogadro's number (\(N_A = 6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1}\)) to get the energy per mole:
\[
