\]

Convert to kJ/mol:
\[
E_{\text{mol}} = \frac{3.990 \times 10^5}{1000} = 399 \, \text{kJ/mol}
\]

The wavelength (300 nm) has three significant figures, so the energy is rounded to 399 kJ/mol. Comparing this to the typical single-bond energy of 400 kJ/mol, the photon energy (399 kJ/mol) is very close, indicating that UV photons of this wavelength can break such bonds.

