Problem: 5.3-15. Three drugs are being tested for use as the treatment of a certain disease. Let $p_1, p_2$, and $p_3$ represent the probabilities of success for the respective drugs. As three patients come in, each is given one of the drugs in a random order. After $n=10$ "triples" and assuming independence, compute the probability that the maximum number of successes with one of the drugs exceeds eight if, in fact, $p_1=p_2=p_3=0.7$
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The problem requires finding the probability that the maximum number of successes with one of the three drugs exceeds eight, given that each drug has a success probability of 0.7, and there are 10 independent triples (each triple uses each drug once).

The number of successes for each drug follows a binomial distribution with \(n = 10\) trials and success probability \(p = 0.7\). Let \(S_1\), \(S_2\), and \(S_3\) represent the number of successes for drugs 1, 2, and 3, respectively.

The probability that the maximum number of successes exceeds eight is \(P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) > 8)\). This is equivalent to \(1 - P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) \leq 8) = 1 - P(S_1 \leq 8, S_2 \leq 8, S_3 \leq 8)\).

Since the drugs are identical and independent, \(P(S_1 \leq 8, S_2 \leq 8, S_3 \leq 8) = [P(S \leq 8)]^3\), where \(S \sim \text{Binomial}(10, 0.7)\).

First, compute \(P(S > 8)\) for a single drug:
- \(P(S = 10) = (0.7)^{10} = 0.0282475249\)
- \(P(S = 9) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3) = 10 \times (0.7)^9 \times 0.3 = 10 \times 0.040353607 \times 0.3 = 0.121060821\)
- \(P(S > 8) = P(S = 9) + P(S = 10) = 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459\)

Then, \(P(S \leq 8) = 1 - P(S > 8) = 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541\).

Now, \(P(\text{all } S_i \leq 8) = (0.8506916541)^3 \approx 0.615625\).

Thus, \(P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) > 8) = 1 - 0.615625 = 0.384375\).

Rounding to three decimal places, the probability is 0.384.

